In the early 20th century, Tom Green County was overwhelmingly Democratic, aligning with the "Solid South" political alignment common throughout the region. For instance, in 1916, the [Democratic Party](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) candidate secured nearly 88% of the vote. This dominance, however, began to show cracks in 1928, when Herbert Hoover, a [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)), surprisingly carried the county, perhaps due to local anti-Catholic sentiment against Al Smith. This proved to be an anomaly initially, with the county reverting to strong Democratic support in the 1930s and 40s.

The mid-20th century marked a more decisive shift. Dwight D. Eisenhower's victory in 1952 was a watershed moment, as he won the county with over 62% of the vote, signaling the beginning of the Republican realignment in [Texas](/Texas). While there were occasional Democratic victories, such as Lyndon B. Johnson's in 1964, the trend toward Republican preference became increasingly pronounced. By the 1970s, the county had firmly entrenched itself in the Republican column, with Richard Nixon winning over 71% in 1972. This trend has continued unabated into the 21st century, culminating in the [2024](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_Texas) election where the Republican candidate garnered over 73% of the vote. The county's political identity is now unequivocally red, a testament to the long, slow, and often predictable, march of political evolution.

